ECLOGUE ΙΙΙ.

THIS eclogue represents (after Theocritus, Idyl iv. and v.) the rivalry in song of two shepherds, Menalcas and Damoetas. After some dispute— and a dash of blackguard ——the decision is left to Palaemon as umpire, and the two rival swains vie in alternate couplets. This form of verse is called Amoebaean (ἀμοιβαῖος, respon-vive). The couplets are wholly disconnected, some of them mere squibs flung out, it is supposed, by the poet at his rivals. Though the Amoebaean verse is Greek, and the poem itself copied from Theocritus, yet the alternate abuse is thoroughly Italian. The Romans were very fond of coarse invective and repartee, and these form the staple of the Salurcz (one of the earliest forms of Latin drama), the Fescennine and Atellane farces, and the Mimes.
